C++ MULTISET STL - INTERVIEW NOTES
=========================================
multiset

Underlying DS : Red-Black Tree
Sorted         : Yes
Duplicates     : Yes
Iterator       : Bidirectional
Insert         : O(log n)
Find           : O(log n)
Erase          : O(log n)
Random Access  : No
Elements Modifiable : No
Duplicate Check : Comparator, not operator==
Iterator Invalidation :
    Insert -> No
    Erase  -> Only erased iterator

User-defined object support in multiset
is exactly the same as set.

Either:

1. Overload operator<
OR
2. Provide custom comparator

Difference:

set      -> equivalent key rejected
multiset -> equivalent key accepted

1. What is multiset?
--------------------
- std::multiset is an associative container in STL.
- Stores elements in SORTED order.
- Allows DUPLICATE elements.

Example:
multiset<int> ms;

Insert:
10, 20, 10, 30

Stored:
10 10 20 30

set vs multiset IMpl diff*****
Internally both set and multiset are typically implemented using a Red-Black Tree.

The main difference is:

set stores unique keys and rejects duplicate insertions,

whereas multiset allows multiple equivalent keys and inserts all of them into the tree.


*****IMP
set::insert()      -> returns pair<iterator,bool>

multiset::insert() -> returns iterator

In set, insertion can fail due to duplicates.

In multiset, insertion never fails because duplicates are allowed.

#include <iostream>
#include <set>
using namespace std;

int main()
{
    set<int> s;

    auto result1 = s.insert(10);
    auto result2 = s.insert(10); // duplicate

    cout << boolalpha;

    cout << "First insert success : "
         << result1.second << endl;

    cout << "Second insert success: "
         << result2.second << endl;

    return 0;
}

What does erase(value) do?

Removes ALL occurrences.

Example:

multiset<int> ms = {10,10,10,20};

ms.erase(10);

Result:

20

Very common question.

How to erase only one occurrence?

auto it = ms.find(10);

if(it != ms.end())
    ms.erase(it);

Result:

Before:
10 10 10 20

After:
10 10 20


